response.clean_text:
{
  "response_text": "The average weekly consumption of skimmed and semi-skimmed milk starts at zero at time step 0. By time step 5, consumption rises sharply to approximately 900. At time step 10, consumption reaches approximately 1250. Between time steps 10 and 25, consumption stabilizes around 1200 to 1250 with minor fluctuations. After time step 25, consumption begins to increase again, reaching approximately 1400 by time step 30. The growth in consumption is driven by social influence and habit formation, with susceptibility to social norms (set at 0.2) and a network structure that facilitates interaction (Watts-Strogatz network with parameter 8). The initial rise aligns with the high initial habit strength (10) and gradual adaptation to perceived health benefits (alt-health-mean-initial of 1.69). The stabilization period reflects equilibrium influenced by cognitive dissonance threshold (0.15) and social conformity (0.28). The subsequent increase suggests renewed consumer sensitivity to health and environmental factors, facilitated by ongoing social interactions (p-interact of 0.3)."
}

